16. It's this notion - that a person's beliefs can be attributed to their need to resolve cognitive dissonance, rather than clear and honest thinking - that has come to be used in common parlance, in situations I'd argue are often not that at all.

15. Everyone experiences "cognitive dissonance" but whether their response to it can be attributed to "cognitive dissonance" depends on whether they take the easy path (altering belief) or the hard one (reconciling beliefs and/or actions).

14. Perhaps - and it's only just occurred to me - part of the confusion stems from the short-hand use of the term "cognitive dissonance" to describe both the psychological conflict and how it is (often) resolved.
Which is the more disruptive, uncomfortable thing for them to do?
13. Again, that doesn't make them RIGHT. It just makes them HONEST.

12. If a person, on the other hand, follows a "more stressful" path - changing their beliefs or behavior, at some possible cost - it is difficult to attribute that outcome to cognitive dissonance, as opposed to a thought process with more clarity and integrity.

11. "Cognitive dissonance" has broader applications beyond a conflict between belief and behavior. But it basically boils down to the idea that people tend to follow the "least stressful" path in resolving conflicts between beliefs, or beliefs vs. actions.
But the point is that people tend to choose the "least stressful" path. But if someone in fact chooses the more stressful path, it's hard to attribute their thinking to "cognitive dissonance".
The broader concept can apply to any discomfort over conflicting beliefs and/or actions. But the classic dilemma involves behavior winning out over beliefs.

10. I would suggest that people who have left their party, or at least gone into internal exile, over Trump may be right or wrong, but are not a product of "cognitive dissonance". Those who remained but changed their tune are more likely to fit that bill.
9. The question is what changed: did beliefs alter to conform with existing behavior, or did behavior alter to comfort with existing beliefs?

8. Whereas a similar radio host who was once skeptical of Trump, but has since altered those views in order to keep their show and their audience, may well be genuine converts, but "cognitive dissonance" might well be in play.

7. So, for instance, it makes no sense to accuse a radio host like @ SykesCharlie of "cognitive dissonance". Whether what he thinks about Trump he is correct or not, he's altered his entire career and way of life to conform to those beliefs.

6. So in politics, saying someone's thinking is due to "cognitive dissonance" implies a lot more than that they're just wrong or misguided. You're saying they've allowed their beliefs to change to conform with their existing behavior or advantage.

5. The classic example is a person who knows smoking is harmful but has a habit of smoking. They are much more likely to rationalize to themselves that smoking really isn't THAT harmful than they are to quit smoking, based on their knowledge.
4. In fact, what frequently happens is that people adjust their beliefs to conform with their behavior.
3. Cognitive dissonance refers to situations where what a person believes and how they behave are in conflict. In theory, a rational person should adjust their behavior to conform with their beliefs.
2. Like the term # fakenews, this is a overly broad and highly misleading use of what the term "cognitive dissonance" actually means, in psychology.
